[1.4 Database Languages]
	- DDL (data-definition language)
		-> specify the database schema
		-> specify additional properties of the data.

	- DML (data-manipulation language)
		-> express database queries and updates

	(1.4.1 Data-Definition Language)
		- data storage and definition
			-> specify the storage structure and access methods used by the db system by a set of statements in a special type of DDL

			-> specifies implementation details of the db schemas, hidden from the users.

		- db systems implement only those integrity constraints that can be tested with minimal overhead.

			1) Domain Constraints
				- integer types, character types, date/time types

				- most elementary form of integrity constraint.
					-> tested easily by the system whenever a new data item is entered into the db.

			2) Referential Integrity
				- ensure that a value that appears in one relation for a given set of attributes also appears in a certain set of attributes in another relation (referential integrity)
					-> when a referential-integrity constraint is violated, the normal procedure is to reject the action that caused the violation.

			3) Authorization
				- differentiate among the users as far as the type of access they are permitted on various data values in the db.
					ex)
						+ read authorization (no modification)
						+ insert authorization (insert, but no modification of existing data)
						+ update authorization (only modification, no deletion)
						+ delete authorization (allows deletion of data)

					-> assign the user all, none, or a combination of these types of authorization.

		* output of the DDL is placed in the "data dictionary".
			-> contains "metadata" (data about data)

			-> special type of table that can be accessed and updated only by the db system itself.

		* db system consults the data dictionary before reading or modifying actual data.

	(1.4.2 The SQL Data-Definition Language)
		- SQL provides a rich DDL that allows one to define tables with data types and integrity constraints.

	(1.4.3 Data-Manipulation Language)
		- language that enables users to access or manipuate data as organized by the appropriate data model.

			1) Retrieval of info stored in the db.
			2) Insertion of new info into the db.
			3) Deletion of info from the db.
			4) Modification of info stored in the db.

		- two types of data-manipulation language

			1) Procedural DMLs
				-> require a user to specify "what" data are needed and "how" to get those data.
					ex)
						"Go to the Customers table, scan each row one by one, check if the city equals 'Seoul' and return those rows."

			2) Declarative DMLs (nonprocedural DMLs)
				-> require a user to specify "what" data are needed "without" specifying how to get those data

		- "query" is a statement requesting the retrieval of information.
			-> "query language": DML that involves info retrieval

	(1.4.4 The SQL Data-Manipulation Language)
		* SQL query language is nonprocedural.

	(1.4.5 Database Access from Application Programs)
		- To access the db, DML statements need to be sent from the host to the db where they will be executed.
			-> commonly done by using an application-program interface (set of procedures) that can be used to send DML and DDL statements to the db and retrieve the results.
